AWS EKS Authentication & RBAC Flow (Hinglish)
1️⃣ IAM Identity (AWS Level)
Cluster ko access karne ke liye pehle aapka IAM User ya IAM Role hona chahiye.
Examples:
IAM User → AWS console ya CLI user
IAM Role → EC2 instance role, service account role, ya cross-account role
2️⃣ aws-auth ConfigMap (EKS Level)
Purpose: Map karta hai IAM identities ko Kubernetes username aur groups ke saath.
Default state: sirf cluster creator aur node IAM roles ko access hota hai.

Default aws-auth ConfigMap:

apiVersion: v1
kind: ConfigMap
metadata:
  name: aws-auth
  namespace: kube-system
data:
  mapRoles: |
    - rolearn: arn:aws:iam::<ACCOUNT_ID>:role/<EKS_NODE_ROLE>
      username: system:node:{{EC2PrivateDNSName}}
      groups:
        - system:bootstrappers
        - system:nodes
  mapUsers: |
    - userarn: arn:aws:iam::<ACCOUNT_ID>:user/<CLUSTER_CREATOR>
      username: admin
      groups:
        - system:masters

Key points:

mapRoles → Nodes ya IAM Roles ko Kubernetes user/groups se map karta hai
mapUsers → IAM Users ko Kubernetes user/groups se map karta hai
Sirf jo identities aws-auth mein hain, wahi cluster access kar sakti hain
3️⃣ Kubernetes RBAC (Cluster Level)
Purpose: Decide karta hai user/group kya actions kar sakte hain cluster mein.
Resources:
Role → ek namespace ke andar permissions
ClusterRole → poore cluster ke liye permissions
RoleBinding → Role ko user/group ke saath bind karta hai namespace mein
ClusterRoleBinding → ClusterRole ko user/group ke saath bind karta hai cluster-wide

Namespace-level example (Role + RoleBinding):

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: Role
metadata:
  namespace: dev
  name: pod-reader
rules:
- apiGroups: [""]
  resources: ["pods"]
  verbs: ["get","list","watch"]

---
apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: RoleBinding
metadata:
  name: read-pods-binding
  namespace: dev
subjects:
- kind: User
  name: devuser         # aws-auth mein jo username hai
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: Role
  name: pod-reader
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io

Cluster-wide example (ClusterRole + ClusterRoleBinding):

apiVersion: rbac.authorization.k8s.io/v1
kind: ClusterRoleBinding
metadata:
  name: cluster-admin-binding
subjects:
- kind: User
  name: adminuser       # aws-auth username
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
roleRef:
  kind: ClusterRole
  name: cluster-admin
  apiGroup: rbac.authorization.k8s.io
4️⃣ Step-by-Step Flow
IAM User/Role
       │
       ▼
aws-auth ConfigMap  --> IAM ko Kubernetes username/group mein map karta hai
       │
       ▼
Kubernetes RBAC (Role/ClusterRole + RoleBinding/ClusterRoleBinding)
       │
       ▼
Allowed actions: pods, deployments, nodes, configmaps etc.

Samajh lo:

IAM identity request bhejti hai cluster ko → Authentication via aws-auth
Kubernetes check karta hai aws-auth ConfigMap
Agar identity exist karti hai → allowed
Agar nahi → denied
RBAC check karta hai → Kya user kya kar sakta hai (namespace ya cluster-wide)
5️⃣ Key Notes (Interview Tips)
Default Admin: Cluster creator IAM user → system:masters group
Nodes: Node IAM roles → system:nodes group
Best Practice: Least privilege → IAM → map in aws-auth → specific RBAC
Cross-Account Access: Map external IAM roles in aws-auth → access allow
6️⃣ Flow Diagram (Hinglish)
        +-----------------+
        |  IAM User/Role  |    <-- AWS Identity
        +--------+--------+
                 |
                 ▼
        +-----------------+
        | aws-auth ConfigMap|   <-- IAM → Kubernetes username/groups
        +--------+--------+
                 |
                 ▼
        +-----------------+
        |    Kubernetes   |
        |      RBAC       |   <-- Role/ClusterRole + Bindings
        +--------+--------+
                 |
                 ▼
      Allowed actions in cluster
   (pods, deployments, nodes, namespaces)
